"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 4–6 (fill)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2kings-4-6-fill.py

Covers 99 missing verses: ch4 (43 missing; v10 exists), ch5 (25 missing; v10,v17 exist),
ch6 (31 missing; v17,v25 exist).

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 4: Prophets' guild (b'nê hannebî'îm) as an ANE institution; debt-slavery law (Exod 21:7)
  as the legal backdrop for v1. The Shunammite guest room furnishings as typical ANE hospitality.
  Gilgal famine and wild gourd toxicity; the feeding miracle at Baal-shalishah and ANE firstfruits.
- Ch 5: Naaman's tsara'at as social disability, not necessarily modern leprosy; the enormous
  diplomatic tribute (ten talents silver = ~750 lb). The Jordan dipping as inversion of Naaman's
  honor-shame expectations. Rimmon as Hadad, the Aramean storm-deity.
- Ch 6: Sons of prophets at Jordan — communal living with Elisha. The iron axe-head miracle
  understood against the scarcity and high cost of iron in the early Israelite period.
  Dothan and Aramean siege strategy; the heavenly host as celestial armies (cf. Josh 5:14).
  The Samaria siege famine: donkey's head price (80 shekels) as economic indicator of extremity.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The woman identifies her husband as a member of the <em>b&rsquo;nê hannebî&rsquo;îm</em>, &lsquo;sons of the prophets&rsquo; — a prophetic guild community associated with Elisha. These were communal groups (cf. 2 Kgs 6:1–7) who lived under the supervision of a prophetic leader; their members were not necessarily blood relatives of Elijah or Elisha but disciples or associates. The legal backdrop is Exod 21:7 (and Lev 25:39–41): Israelite debt-slavery law permitted a creditor to seize a debtor&rsquo;s children as bond-servants when the debt could not be paid. The widow&rsquo;s appeal to Elisha is a patronage appeal — she invokes her husband&rsquo;s loyalty to the prophetic community as a claim on Elisha&rsquo;s intercession.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Olive oil was a primary commodity in the ancient Near East — used for cooking, lighting (lamp fuel), cosmetics, medicinal purposes, and temple ritual. The widow&rsquo;s single jar (<em>ʾāsûḵ</em>, a container for anointing oil) is a marginal supply, barely enough for personal use. Elisha&rsquo;s instructions to gather empty vessels from neighbors engage the village economy: such borrowing was a recognized social practice in which community solidarity partially buffered individual economic collapse.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s instruction to borrow &lsquo;empty containers&rsquo; and &lsquo;not too few&rsquo; (<em>ʾal-tamʿîṭî</em>) frames the miracle as contingent on the widow&rsquo;s faith and initiative — the number of vessels gathered would determine the volume of oil produced. This structure — where the scope of divine provision tracks the human act of prepared receptivity — appears also in the widow of Zarephath account (1 Kgs 17) and in Gospel multiplication narratives. ANE parallel: the goddess Asherah was associated with oil abundance, but the text deliberately attributes the provision to YHWH through the prophetic word alone.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The instruction to &lsquo;shut the door behind you and your sons&rsquo; withdraws the miracle from public view — a pattern in Elisha&rsquo;s ministry (cf. 2 Kgs 4:33, where he also shuts the door in the Shunammite resurrection account). The closed-door setting emphasizes that the miracle is not a public spectacle or a demonstration of prophetic power but a private act of provision. The woman&rsquo;s sons function as assistants; their presence links the miracle to the family unit that would otherwise be enslaved.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The narrative slows to emphasize repetition — &lsquo;they kept bringing vessels while she kept pouring&rsquo; — using the Hebrew imperfect to convey continued action. The scene is entirely domestic: mother and sons working in an enclosed space with borrowed household equipment. The extraordinary emerges within the ordinary rhythms of village labor. Neighbors&rsquo; vessels represent the entire social network the family could access; when those are exhausted, the provision ceases.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The oil stops precisely when the last borrowed vessel is filled — not before, not after. This detail underlines the interpretive framework established by v3: the scale of provision matched the scope of preparation. The widow&rsquo;s statement &lsquo;there are no more vessels&rsquo; functions as the natural limiting condition; the miracle operates within the constraints of the human response. Comparable ANE royal inscriptions sometimes attribute agricultural abundance to divine favor, but those are idealized propaganda; this account is intimate and economically specific.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s solution is practical: sell the oil, pay the debt, live on the surplus. The language of debt-payment (<em>šallᵉmî ʾet-niššayēḵ</em>) uses the same root (<em>šālem</em>) as <em>shalom</em> — debt cancellation as a form of restoration and wholeness. The surplus oil that remains after debt payment provides ongoing subsistence for the widow and her sons. The miracle does not make the family wealthy; it cancels their liability and re-establishes their social standing in the community.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Shunem (modern Sulam) is a village in the Jezreel Valley in Issachar, some 15–20 km from Carmel. A &lsquo;great woman&rsquo; (<em>ʾiššâ gᵉdôlāh</em>) denotes high social standing — wealth, land-ownership, and community influence, not merely personal virtue. Her pressing Elisha to eat (using a verb of urgency, <em>ḥāzaq</em>) is hospitality initiative consistent with ANE aristocratic norms: receiving a known prophet was an act of honor and an invitation to divine favor. The Shunammite becomes a patron to the itinerant prophet.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s declaration that Elisha is &lsquo;a holy man of God&rsquo; (<em>ʾîš &rsquo;ĕlōhîm qādôš hûʾ</em>) uses the full honorific that marks prophetic office. The term <em>qādôš</em> (holy) is rare as a human descriptor in the Hebrew Bible — it signals that Elisha is set apart for divine service in a way that is perceptible to a discerning observer. The Shunammite&rsquo;s theological discernment contrasts with the king&rsquo;s and other officials&rsquo; tendency to miss the prophetic presence; she acts on what she perceives.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The guest room Elisha uses when passing through Shunem becomes the setting for the subsequent death-and-resurrection narrative (vv. 18–37). The narrative marker &lsquo;one day he came there, went up to the room, and rested&rsquo; establishes the routine of his visits. The prophet&rsquo;s reliance on the Shunammite&rsquo;s hospitality inverts normal patron-client dynamics: she provides; he will ultimately provide the gift she did not ask for (a son) and cannot replace (the son&rsquo;s life).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elisha communicates through Gehazi his servant rather than directly with the Shunammite woman — a protocol detail that reflects ancient hierarchies. Speaking through an intermediary maintains social distance appropriate to a single male prophet and a married woman; Gehazi becomes the official channel of communication. The Shunammite&rsquo;s social standing is evident: she &lsquo;stood before him&rsquo; (<em>wattaʿămod lᵉpānāyw</em>) — the posture of a social equal presenting herself at a formal audience, not the posture of a supplicant.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s offer to intercede with the king or the commander of the army reveals the prophet&rsquo;s access to royal and military networks. The offer implies that the Shunammite woman might have legal or property disputes that required royal adjudication — a common anxiety for a wealthy woman in an honor-shame society where land tenure depended on male advocacy. Her reply &lsquo;I dwell among my own people&rsquo; (<em>bᵉtôḵ ʿammî ʾānōḵî yōšābet</em>) is a declaration that her social situation is secure; she does not need political patronage.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Gehazi identifies the Shunammite&rsquo;s barrenness and her husband&rsquo;s old age — the double obstacle to an heir that placed her in a position of social vulnerability despite her current prosperity. Childlessness in the ancient Near East meant the eventual loss of property (no male heir to inherit), social marginalization in widowhood, and the extinction of the husband&rsquo;s family name. The situation precisely mirrors the Abraham-Sarah narrative (Gen 18:10–14) and the Hannah narrative (1 Sam 1); barrenness resolved by prophetic word is a recurring structural pattern in Hebrew narrative.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Elisha calls the Shunammite and she &lsquo;stood in the doorway&rsquo; (<em>wattaʿămod bappetaḥ</em>) — the threshold position that marks liminal encounters in Hebrew narrative. Standing at a doorway signals that the encounter is formal and momentous; the same posture appears at thresholds in other prophetic narratives. The shift from Gehazi as intermediary to Elisha addressing her directly signals that what follows transcends ordinary social exchange.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s protest &lsquo;do not deceive your servant&rsquo; (<em>ʾal-tᵉkazzēb bᵉšipḥātekā</em>) is not unbelief but appropriate caution: in the ANE world, raising and then dashing a barren woman&rsquo;s hope of a child was a recognized cruelty. She is protecting herself from disappointment. The word for deceive (<em>kāzab</em>) is the opposite of prophetic truthfulness; she is, in effect, asking Elisha to confirm that this is a genuine prophetic word and not false consolation. The language echoes the Abrahamic annunciation where Sarah also expresses incredulity (Gen 18:12–15).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The fulfillment is dated to &lsquo;about this time next year&rsquo; (<em>kāʿēt ḥayyâ</em>) — the same idiom used in Gen 18:10 and 14 for the Isaac annunciation. The verbal echo signals that the narrator is deliberately placing this account in the trajectory of the Abrahamic barrenness-and-birth pattern. The Shunammite becomes another figure in the series of women — Sarah, Rebekah, Rachel, Hannah — whose barrenness is overcome by divine promise and whose sons carry forward significant roles in Israel&rsquo;s story.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The child grows to the age when he can accompany his father to the harvest field — an economic unit of participation typical of agrarian societies. Children in ANE agricultural households participated in harvest work from an early age; the harvest scene establishes a normal, functioning family life before catastrophe strikes. The juxtaposition of the fulfilled promise (a growing child) with the sudden collapse (vv. 19–20) intensifies the narrative tension.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&lsquo;My head! My head!&rsquo; (<em>rōʾšî rōʾšî</em>) — the doubled cry signals acute distress; in the harvest field context, heatstroke is the most plausible medical cause. Harvest work in the Jezreel Valley in summer involves intense sun exposure; sudden collapse from heat injury was a recognized danger. The father&rsquo;s instruction to carry the child to his mother follows expected domestic protocol: medical crises within the household were managed in the women&rsquo;s sphere.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The child dies at noon — the time of maximum heat in the agricultural day. The child&rsquo;s death &lsquo;on her lap&rsquo; establishes the most intimate possible setting; the Shunammite is positioned as both caregiver and the one who must now act. Her response — going up to the prophet&rsquo;s room and laying the child on Elisha&rsquo;s bed (v21) — is a deliberate prophetic claim: the place associated with divine presence is the appropriate location for a miracle she has not yet stopped expecting.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Placing the dead child on the prophet&rsquo;s bed is a significant act — it appropriates the sacred space of the man of God for a petition that has not yet been spoken. The Shunammite does not mourn publicly or prepare the child for burial; she acts as one who believes the story is not finished. ANE parallels: the beds and sleeping chambers of holy men were treated as spaces of concentrated divine power; placing the dead there could be understood as making a ritual claim on that power.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s request for a servant and donkey frames a journey of about 25–30 km to Carmel — not a quick trip. Her instruction to send &lsquo;quickly&rsquo; (<em>ûmāhartî wᵉhālaḵtî</em>) establishes urgency without explaining why. She conceals her purpose from her husband, whose practical objection follows in v23. The donkey as transport animal is consistent with her elevated social standing; it was the standard vehicle for persons of means in the Israelite period.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The husband&rsquo;s question &lsquo;Why go to him today? It is neither a new moon nor a Sabbath&rsquo; reveals that pilgrimages to prophets typically occurred on festival days — new moon (<em>ḥōdeš</em>) and Sabbath (<em>šabbāt</em>) were the recognized times for consulting a man of God. This detail illuminates the calendar of prophetic accessibility in monarchic Israel: prophets were not always available; they received visitors on holy days. The Shunammite&rsquo;s visit on an ordinary day marks the emergency she refuses to name.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s instruction to the servant &lsquo;do not slow down unless I tell you&rsquo; reflects the urgency of the situation. The word for &lsquo;slow down&rsquo; (<em>ʿāṣōr baʿădî rᵉḵōb&rsquo;) concerns restraining the donkey&rsquo;s pace; she is pressing for maximum speed within the limits of the animal. The overland route from Shunem to Mount Carmel crosses the Jezreel Valley — perhaps four to six hours of travel. Every element of her preparation is purposeful and urgent.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Mount Carmel had long associations with prophetic activity (cf. 1 Kgs 18, the Elijah-Baal contest) and apparently served as one of Elisha&rsquo;s regular stations. The sight of the Shunammite &lsquo;coming in the distance&rsquo; (seen from the high ground of Carmel) prompted Elisha&rsquo;s prophetic discernment that something was wrong: &lsquo;Her soul is bitter&rsquo; (<em>wᵉnapšāh mārat lāh</em>, v27). Prophetic intuition of spiritual distress is a standard feature of the prophetic narratives; Elisha perceives what Gehazi cannot.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Elisha sends Gehazi ahead with a standard welfare query: is it well with you (<em>hăšālôm lāḵ</em>)? The triple inquiry — &lsquo;with you? with your husband? with the child?&rsquo; — follows the conventional pattern of village greeting that moved through the household unit. The Shunammite&rsquo;s response &lsquo;All is well (<em>šālôm</em>)&rsquo; is a deliberate suspension of disclosure — she is reserving her petition for Elisha himself, not his intermediary, even as she speaks the opposite of the truth about the child&rsquo;s condition.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s seizure of Elisha&rsquo;s feet (<em>wattaḥăzēq bᵉraglāyw</em>) is the posture of urgent petition — prostration at the feet of a superior. Gehazi&rsquo;s impulse to push her away reflects protocol norms; such contact with a holy man was considered inappropriate without invitation. Elisha&rsquo;s counter-instruction &lsquo;leave her alone&rsquo; overrides normal social restraint and signals that the prophetic encounter is to proceed without barriers. His acknowledgment that YHWH has &lsquo;hidden it from me&rsquo; is a rare statement of prophetic limitation.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s reproach &lsquo;Did I ask my lord for a son?&rsquo; recalls her initial caution at v16. She had warned against false hope; now the fulfilled promise has been reversed. Her complaint is formally a qal waḥomer (a fortiori) argument: if I did not request this gift, how much more grievous is its loss? The theological tension — God gave, God (through the prophet) apparently took away — is not resolved here; it is the engine driving the subsequent miracle.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s instruction to Gehazi to &lsquo;tuck your garment into your belt&rsquo; (<em>ḥăgōr motnêḵā</em>) is the standard preparation for urgent travel in the ancient world — gathering up the long robe to free the legs for running. The prohibition on greeting anyone en route reflects an urgency that overrides normal social courtesy (cf. Luke 10:4, where Jesus uses similar language for the seventy). The staff as an extension of prophetic power (cf. Moses&rsquo; staff; Elisha&rsquo;s own earlier use in 2:14) makes Gehazi&rsquo;s mission a preliminary attempt at mediated restoration.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The Shunammite&rsquo;s oath &lsquo;As the LORD lives and as you yourself live&rsquo; (<em>ḥay-yhwh wᵉḥay-napšᵉkā</em>) is the strongest available oath formula in Hebrew; it invokes the life of God and the prophet&rsquo;s own life as guarantors that she will not be dismissed with a proxy. Her refusal to let Elisha remain on Carmel without accompanying her is a demand for direct prophetic presence — not mediated power through a staff. Elisha complies; personal accompaniment becomes necessary for the miracle.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gehazi&rsquo;s staff laid on the boy&rsquo;s face produces no response — &lsquo;no sound and no sign of life&rsquo; (<em>wᵉqôl wᵉʾên qešeb</em>). The failure of the proximate, impersonal method establishes that the resurrection requires the prophet&rsquo;s direct bodily presence. This structural pattern — failed preliminary attempt followed by successful personal intervention — appears also in 1 Kgs 17:21 (Elijah&rsquo;s resurrection of the Zarephath widow&rsquo;s son), indicating shared narrative convention for prophetic resurrection accounts in Kings.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The scene at the house — the child lying dead on the prophet&rsquo;s own bed — sets up the confrontation with death in the private sacred space. Ancient Near Eastern background: the sleeping chambers of gods (in temple ideology) or holy men were associated with life-giving power; placing the dead child there was the Shunammite&rsquo;s implicit claim on that power. The detail that the bed is specifically Elisha&rsquo;s (<em>miškāb hāʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) is not incidental — it establishes the ritual claim.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s prayer in the closed room mirrors Elijah&rsquo;s pattern in 1 Kgs 17:20–21; prophetic resurrection involves direct address to YHWH in private. The closed door (as also in v4&rsquo;s oil miracle) is a Sitz im Leben of prophetic concentration — withdrawal from the public sphere to address YHWH. The two-stage pattern of Elisha&rsquo;s prayer (v33) followed by physical action (v34) reflects the view that resurrection power flows from YHWH in response to prophetic petition rather than from the prophet&rsquo;s own power.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s act of lying on the child — mouth to mouth, eyes to eyes, hands to hands (<em>pîw ʿal-pîw wᵉʿênāyw ʿal-ʿênāyw wᵉkappāyw ʿal-kappāyw</em>) — matches exactly Elijah&rsquo;s action in 1 Kgs 17:21, establishing Elisha as Elijah&rsquo;s true successor who performs the same acts of power. This physical positioning is not a primitive medical procedure (though the specificity is noted in medical history); it is a prophetic act of complete identification with the dead child, transmitting prophetic life-power through contact. The child&rsquo;s flesh warming indicates the gradual return of life.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The two-stage miracle — Elisha rises, walks back and forth, then stretches over the child a second time — follows a pattern of prophetic persistence. The child&rsquo;s sneezing seven times before opening his eyes is a detail of biological verisimilitude that has no ANE parallel. The number seven has conventional completeness in Hebrew idiom, but sneezing as a sign of returning life appears in some ancient texts (cf. the Egyptian story of Setne and the sneezing revived person). The physical detail anchors the miracle in observed bodily experience.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s instruction &lsquo;Take up your son&rsquo; (<em>śᵉʾî binnēḵ</em>) in the third person through Gehazi restores normal social protocol after the miracle — the Shunammite is now addressed as a mother receiving her child, not as a petitioner receiving a prophetic gift. The mother&rsquo;s falling at Elisha&rsquo;s feet (<em>wattipōl ʿal-raglāyw</em>) is gratitude in the same posture as petition (v27) — she who seized his feet in desperate appeal now bows before him in thanksgiving.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The Shunammite &lsquo;went out&rsquo; with her son — the narrative closure returns her to the domestic space without further explanation. The economy of the ending is deliberate: the account is complete when the gift is restored; theological reflection is not supplied. The reader is expected to draw the connection between YHWH as the giver and restorer of life (v14–17 as promise; vv. 32–37 as fulfillment) and the prophetic role as mediator of that life-power.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Gilgal (probably the one near Jericho, one of Elisha&rsquo;s circuit stops; cf. 2:1) during a famine — famines are periodically attested in the Levant through both biblical and extrabiblical sources. The &lsquo;sons of the prophets sitting before him&rsquo; (<em>yōšᵉbîm lᵉpānāyw</em>) describes a teaching or consultative session in the prophetic community. Elisha&rsquo;s instruction to cook a large pot (<em>sir haggādōl</em>) for the group reflects communal meal-sharing within the prophetic guild.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The &lsquo;wild vine&rsquo; and the wild gourds gathered from it (<em>paqquʿōt śādeh</em>) are most commonly identified with the colocynth (<em>Citrullus colocynthis</em>), a desert plant producing attractive but intensely bitter and violently purgative fruit. In famine conditions, wild foods were gathered indiscriminately; the gatherer&rsquo;s inexperience or desperation leads him to collect a harmful plant. The gourds sliced into the stew introduce a toxin that would produce acute gastric distress consistent with the men&rsquo;s reaction.</p>",
    "40": "<p>&lsquo;Death in the pot&rsquo; (<em>māwet bassîr</em>) — the men recognize the bitter, burning taste characteristic of colocynth poisoning. ANE herbal knowledge included recognition of toxic plants; the immediate identification and the refusal to eat further indicates practical culinary experience. The men&rsquo;s appeal to Elisha as &lsquo;man of God&rsquo; frames the situation as a crisis requiring prophetic intervention — they cannot consume their only available food.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s use of flour (<em>qemaḥ</em>) to neutralize the toxin has generated discussion about its mode of action. The text does not present this as chemical neutralization but as a prophetic sign-act: the flour is the vehicle of the miracle, not its cause. Similar sign-acts where an unlikely material mediates divine power appear throughout Elisha&rsquo;s ministry (salt purifying the spring in 2:21; a stick making iron float in 6:6). The point is that YHWH acts through prophetic command even using ordinary materials.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Baal-shalishah — a location in Ephraim (cf. 1 Sam 9:4), distinct from the great cult center Baal-Peor. The name&rsquo;s connection to the Baalized toponymy of northern Israel is noted but does not affect the account. The offering of twenty barley loaves from firstfruits (<em>leḥem bikkûrîm</em>) is significant: firstfruits were consecrated to YHWH and typically brought to a sanctuary or a recognized representative of divine service. Bringing firstfruits to Elisha confirms his status as the legitimate locus of prophetic-priestly authority in the northern kingdom during this period.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The servant&rsquo;s objection &lsquo;How can I set this before a hundred men?&rsquo; establishes the scarcity: twenty loaves for a hundred people is a fifth of normal provision. Elisha&rsquo;s response — &lsquo;Give it to the people to eat, for thus says the LORD&rsquo; — invokes the prophetic formula (<em>kōh ʾāmar yhwh</em>) as the ground for an impossible instruction. The multiplication miracle with its &lsquo;and they had some left over&rsquo; (cf. John 6:12–13) follows the same pattern as the widow&rsquo;s oil: divine provision exceeds the apparent limit.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The closing &lsquo;according to the word of the LORD&rsquo; (<em>kidbar yhwh</em>) attributes the multiplication explicitly to YHWH&rsquo;s word spoken through Elisha. The Baal-shalishah feeding functions as a prophetic sign in the tradition of the wilderness manna: YHWH provides for his people through the prophetic word even in conditions of scarcity. The detail of &lsquo;some left over&rsquo; echoes the wilderness surplus (Exod 16:17–18) and anticipates Gospel multiplication accounts where surplus remainder confirms the divine origin of the provision.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Naaman (<em>naʿămān</em>, &lsquo;pleasantness&rsquo;) is the commander of the Aramean army — <em>śar-ṣᵉbāʾ melek ʾărām</em> — at a time when Aram-Damascus was the dominant power in the southern Levant. The text&rsquo;s note that &lsquo;through him the LORD had given victory to Aram&rsquo; (<em>bô nātan-yhwh tᵉšûʿâ lᵃʾărām</em>) is theologically audacious: YHWH is credited with military victories for a foreign nation, suggesting that YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty extends to international politics, not merely Israelite history. His <em>tsara&rsquo;at</em> — traditionally translated leprosy but more broadly a skin condition causing ritual impurity — would have been a severe disability in a military and court context, affecting his social role without necessarily incapacitating him physically (he is still active as commander).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Aramean raiding parties (<em>gᵉdûdîm</em>) into Israel took captives as labor and tribute. The &lsquo;little girl&rsquo; (<em>naʿărāh qᵉṭannāh</em>) who serves Naaman&rsquo;s wife has been separated from her family and homeland by slave raid — a routine feature of Iron Age warfare in the Levant, documented in Assyrian records as well as biblical narrative. Her ethnic identity as Israelite is significant: the knowledge of YHWH&rsquo;s prophet in Samaria exists at the margins of Aramean power, carried by a nameless enslaved child. The narrative&rsquo;s structure places the reversal of Israel&rsquo;s powerlessness in the mouth of its most vulnerable member.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The girl&rsquo;s declaration — &lsquo;if only my lord were before the prophet in Samaria&rsquo; — is expressed as a wish (<em>lû</em> + jussive), reflecting her limited authority to initiate action. Her confident assertion that the prophet &lsquo;would cure him of his leprosy&rsquo; (<em>wᵉʾāsap ʾōtô mitstsāraʿtô</em>) frames prophetic healing as known fact, not speculation. A slave&rsquo;s testimony in an aristocratic household would normally carry little weight, but the urgency of Naaman&rsquo;s condition elevates any potential solution. The transmission of prophetic reputation across ethnic and political boundaries — from an Israelite slave to an Aramean general — illustrates how YHWH&rsquo;s name circulates in the international sphere.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s report to the king of Aram treats the slave girl&rsquo;s testimony as actionable intelligence. The chain of authority — slave girl → Naaman&rsquo;s wife → Naaman → king of Aram — illustrates how information flowed through hierarchical ANE court structures. That the word of a foreign Israelite slave girl reaches the king of Aram and initiates a diplomatic mission indicates the credibility that Elisha&rsquo;s reputation had achieved, even in enemy territory.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The gift Naaman brings for his healing is enormous by any measure: ten talents of silver (approximately 340 kg or 750 lb), six thousand shekels of gold (approximately 70 kg or 150 lb), and ten changes of clothing — a multi-year national budget for a small city-state. This level of payment reflects both the value placed on healing from <em>tsara&rsquo;at</em> (which carried social and cultic exclusion) and the ANE convention that supernatural services — including the services of diviners, dream interpreters, and healers — commanded proportional payment. The king of Aram frames the mission as a diplomatic visit with a commercial dimension, not as a religious consultation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The letter from the king of Aram to the king of Israel treats the healing transaction as a royal matter: king to king. The phrasing &lsquo;I have sent you my servant Naaman that you may cure him&rsquo; creates a diplomatic trap: if the king of Israel cannot or will not comply, it becomes a casus belli. ANE royal correspondence (extensively documented in the Amarna letters from the 14th century BCE) frequently deployed this form — using diplomatic language to create obligations that could not easily be refused without offense.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The king of Israel&rsquo;s tearing of garments (<em>wayyiqraʿ ʾet-bᵉgādāyw</em>) is the standard mourning-and-distress gesture in the Hebrew Bible, here used to express political panic rather than grief. His rhetorical question — &lsquo;Am I God, able to kill and to make alive?&rsquo; (<em>hăʾĕlōhîm ʾānî lᵉmāmît ûlᵉhaḥăyôt</em>) — inadvertently makes the correct theological point: healing leprosy is a divine prerogative. His suspicion that the request is a pretext for war reflects the volatile political context of the Aramean-Israelite relationship (cf. 1 Kgs 20; 22). He does not think of Elisha, who is the actual locus of divine power.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s message to the king — &lsquo;Let him come to me, and he shall know that there is a prophet in Israel&rsquo; (<em>wᵉyēdaʿ kî yēš nābîʾ bᵉyiśrāʾēl</em>) — reframes the encounter from a political to a prophetic event. The phrase &lsquo;there is a prophet in Israel&rsquo; asserts that Israel&rsquo;s real resource in this situation is not royal diplomacy but the presence of a man of God. Elisha inserts himself into the diplomatic chain and takes responsibility for the outcome — a bold prophetic claim in the face of an international crisis.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Naaman arrives at Elisha&rsquo;s house with full military retinue — horses and chariots (<em>bᵉsûsāyw ûbᵉriḵbô</em>) — displaying his rank and the Aramean king&rsquo;s investment in the mission. The scene is staged for maximum contrast: Aramean military power at the door of an Israelite prophet&rsquo;s house. Elisha does not come out to meet him — a deliberate protocol reversal. In ANE royal and elite culture, the greater power would be received; Elisha&rsquo;s non-appearance signals that the expected social hierarchies are suspended.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s anger reflects the violation of honor-shame expectations: he anticipated a formal healing ritual — the prophet would &lsquo;come out to me in person, stand and call on the name of the LORD his God, and wave his hand over the spot&rsquo; (<em>yāṣōʾ yāṣōʾ wᵉʿāmad wᵉqārāʾ bᵉšēm yhwh ʾĕlōhāyw&rsquo;). This expected gesture — hand-waving over the afflicted area — is attested in ANE magical healing texts from Mesopotamia and Egypt. Naaman expected a performance appropriate to his status as a great man; the messenger&rsquo;s instruction violated both the expected ritual form and the expected social deference.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s mention of the Abana and Pharpar rivers (the main rivers of Damascus, modern Barada and Nahr al-Awaj) as superior to &lsquo;all the waters of Israel&rsquo; is not simply nationalistic pride but reflects genuine hydrological superiority: the rivers of the Damascus oasis were perennially flowing, cold mountain streams, while the Jordan was a slower, lowland river, murkier in places. From a pragmatic standpoint, Naaman&rsquo;s assessment is reasonable. His rejection of the Jordan is also a rejection of what the Jordan represents — the distinctive body of water associated with Israel&rsquo;s crossing into the land and Elijah&rsquo;s crossing in 2:8.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s servants address him with the honorific &lsquo;my father&rsquo; (<em>ʾābî</em>) — a term of respectful address that could be used by subordinates for a senior authority figure. Their logic is a <em>qal waḥomer</em>: if you would do something hard for the prophet, how much more something easy? The question &lsquo;how much more, then, when he says to you, Wash and be clean?&rsquo; reverses his expectation — the very ease of the instruction should recommend it. The servants&rsquo; counsel prevails over Naaman&rsquo;s pride; in the narrative structure, it is the subordinate voices (the slave girl in v3; the servants here) who carry the true prophetic message.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Jordan dipping seven times — a number of completeness in Hebrew idiom — is specifically prescribed by the prophetic word; deviating from the number (stopping at five, say) would presumably not have achieved the result. Naaman&rsquo;s restoration — &lsquo;his flesh was restored like the flesh of a young child&rsquo; (<em>wayyāšob bᵉśārô kᵉbᵉśar naʿar qāṭōn</em>) — uses language of reversal: what was corrupted and aging is returned to a state of youth and wholeness. This is not merely medical cure but social and cultic rehabilitation: healed from <em>tsara&rsquo;at</em> meant re-entry into community, worship, and normal social function.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s confession — &lsquo;I know that there is no God in all the earth except in Israel&rsquo; (<em>hinnēh-nāʾ yādaʿtî kî ʾên ʾĕlōhîm bᵉḵol-hāʾāreṣ kî ʾim-bᵉyiśrāʾēl</em>) — is a monotheistic declaration by a foreigner, comparable to Rahab&rsquo;s confession (Josh 2:11) and the queen of Sheba&rsquo;s acknowledgment (1 Kgs 10:9). The returned &lsquo;gift&rsquo; (<em>bᵉrāḵāh</em>, blessing) offered to Elisha indicates that Naaman now understands the healing as YHWH&rsquo;s act through a prophet, not a commercial transaction. The pattern — Gentile healed, Gentile confesses YHWH — is later cited by Jesus as a sign of YHWH&rsquo;s universal sovereignty (Luke 4:27).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s refusal of payment — sworn by the oath &lsquo;As the LORD lives, before whom I stand&rsquo; (<em>ḥay-yhwh ʾăšer-ʿāmadtî lᵉpānāyw</em>) — distinguishes prophetic service from the commercial healing that characterized professional diviners and physicians in the ANE world. Prophets in Israel were sometimes paid (1 Sam 9:7–8; cf. Balaam), but Elisha here refuses on principle: accepting payment from Naaman would suggest that the healing was a commercial service rather than a sign of YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign grace operating through the prophet. The refusal also prevents any equation of YHWH&rsquo;s power with marketable Aramean goods.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s request for prophetic tolerance of his continued attendance in the temple of Rimmon addresses a real dilemma for a foreign monotheist in an official position. Rimmon is the storm-deity Hadad (the name &lsquo;Rimmon&rsquo; or <em>Rammān</em> means &lsquo;Thunderer&rsquo;), the principal deity of Aram-Damascus, analogous to Baal in Canaan and Adad in Mesopotamia. As commander and presumably a royal official, Naaman was expected to participate in state religious ceremonies. His request — &lsquo;may the LORD pardon your servant in this matter&rsquo; — is not cynical compromise but a sincere anticipation of moral conflict and a request for prophetic ruling on the permissibility of his situation.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s response &lsquo;Go in peace&rsquo; (<em>lēḵ lᵉšālôm</em>) is a standard farewell formula but carries significant weight here: it is not a rebuke, a prohibition, or a condition. The text does not amplify with any ruling on the Rimmon question; Elisha simply dismisses Naaman in peace. This ambiguity has generated extensive discussion: some interpreters see it as tacit tolerance of accommodation under constraint; others as a simple farewell without implied endorsement. The narrative leaves the question open, perhaps deliberately. Naaman departs as a confessing monotheist navigating a complex diplomatic role — a liminal figure the text does not condemn.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Gehazi&rsquo;s interior monologue reveals the commercial logic he applies to the encounter: his master has let Naaman &lsquo;off without accepting what he brought&rsquo; — the massive gift of silver, gold, and clothing represents an enormous windfall foregone. The phrase &lsquo;as the LORD lives, I will run after him and accept something from him&rsquo; parodies Elisha&rsquo;s oath formula in v16 — Gehazi invokes YHWH&rsquo;s name in support of the very commercial transaction Elisha refused in YHWH&rsquo;s name. The irony is sharp: Gehazi claims YHWH&rsquo;s authority for greed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Naaman sees Gehazi running after him and steps down from his chariot to meet him — the gesture of social consideration toward someone of lower status signals Naaman&rsquo;s genuine transformation. His question &lsquo;Is everything all right?&rsquo; (<em>hăšālôm</em>) echoes the welfare formula of v26 and establishes the ironic contrast: Naaman, newly cleansed and confessing, extends considerate inquiry; Gehazi, standing in the prophetic household, is about to commit fraud.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Gehazi&rsquo;s fabricated story — two young prophets have arrived and Elisha needs silver and clothing for them — invents a plausible prophetic-community need to justify the request. The &lsquo;company of the prophets from the hill country of Ephraim&rsquo; is a geographically plausible reference; prophetic guilds were known in that region. Gehazi requests a fraction of what Naaman offered (one talent of silver vs. ten), making the deception seem modest and therefore credible. The request for clothing is particularly apt, since Naaman&rsquo;s gift had specifically included it.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Naaman&rsquo;s generosity in insisting on giving two talents rather than the one requested reflects his gratitude and the enormous surplus of what he brought. Two talents of silver is still a staggering sum — equivalent to perhaps 70 kg of silver — far more than needed for any plausible prophetic community need. Naaman ties the silver in two bags and assigns two of his own servants to carry them back with Gehazi — a courtesy to the assumed prophets of Israel, and an inadvertent witness to Gehazi&rsquo;s deception.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&lsquo;The hill&rsquo; (<em>hāʿōpel</em>) refers to a specific elevated part of the approach to the city — possibly the Ophel, though the northern Israel context makes a different location more likely. Gehazi takes the bags from Naaman&rsquo;s servants, deposits them inside, and sends the servants back — all before presenting himself to Elisha. The concealment and the sequential actions indicate premeditation, not impulsive theft. Gehazi is methodically managing the cover of his deception.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s question &lsquo;Where have you been, Gehazi?&rsquo; and Gehazi&rsquo;s denial &lsquo;Your servant hasn&rsquo;t been anywhere&rsquo; sets up the prophetic exposure that follows. The denial uses a strong Hebrew idiom of absence: <em>lōʾ-hālaḵ ʿabdᵉḵā ʾānnâ wᵉʾānnâ</em>, &lsquo;your servant did not go anywhere at all.&rsquo; The redundancy intensifies the lie. Elisha&rsquo;s knowledge of Gehazi&rsquo;s movements — &lsquo;did not my heart go with you?&rsquo; (v26) — reflects the prophetic omniscience that makes deception futile; the prophet sees what the servant thinks is hidden.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&lsquo;Is this the time to accept silver, clothing, olive groves, vineyards, sheep, oxen, and servants?&rsquo; (<em>hāʿēt lāqaḥat et-hakkesep wᵉlāqaḥat bᵉgādîm</em>) — Elisha&rsquo;s list expands far beyond what Gehazi actually received, describing the full range of wealth accumulation. The prophetic critique targets not just this specific act but the mercenary orientation it represents. The &lsquo;time&rsquo; (<em>ʿēt</em>) argument draws on prophetic calendrical consciousness: this was the moment when Naaman had been healed and confessed YHWH; commodifying that moment by accepting payment corrupts the witness value of the healing.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The transfer of Naaman&rsquo;s leprosy to Gehazi and his descendants is the judicial sentence that closes the account. &lsquo;Cling to you and your descendants forever&rsquo; (<em>tidbaq-bᵉḵā ûbᵉzarʿᵃḵā lᵉʿôlām</em>) — the same condition Naaman was healed of becomes the permanent mark of the servant&rsquo;s betrayal. The irony is structural: Gehazi traded the healing miracle for silver, and the miracle is reversed against him. Naaman goes away white-skinned no more (<em>wᵉhûʾ mᵉṣōrāʿ kaššāleg</em>); Gehazi goes away &lsquo;white as snow&rsquo; — carrying what the Aramean commander left behind.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The sons of the prophets (<em>b&rsquo;nê hannebî&rsquo;îm</em>) describe their living space as &lsquo;too cramped&rsquo; (<em>tsār mimmennû</em>) — a growing community around Elisha whose housing needs have exceeded the current facility. This casual detail illuminates the prophetic-guild structure: these were residential communities, not solitary ascetics. The setting near the Jordan (v2) and the presumably modest accommodation suggest a community of intentional simplicity that is nonetheless a genuine social institution with practical needs.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The proposal to go to the Jordan and &lsquo;each get a log&rsquo; (<em>wᵉniqqaḥ miššām ʾîš qôrâ ʾeḥāt</em>) for building reflects the availability of timber near the Jordan riparian zone. The Jordan Valley in this period had denser vegetation than today; riverside timber was accessible, though large stands of forest were already depleted in much of Canaan. The communal self-help building project — each member responsible for one log — reflects the egalitarian labor-sharing of prophetic guild community life.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The request that Elisha accompany his servants — &lsquo;Please come with your servants&rsquo; — and his compliance are noted as an act of prophetic solidarity. Elisha participates in the physical labor and relocation of his community rather than remaining at a distance as a purely spiritual authority. His willingness to go with them places him in proximity to the subsequent crisis (the lost axe head) where his intervention is needed.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The narrative economy of the journey to the Jordan is typical of prophetic-cycle accounts: the minimum detail necessary to establish the setting. &lsquo;They began cutting down trees&rsquo; (<em>wᵉyiggᵉzᵉrû hāʿēṣîm</em>) — the work begins immediately upon arrival. The communal nature of the work is implied by the plural subject; the individual whose axe head falls (v5) is one member of this collective project.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The axe head falling into the water was a genuine crisis in the Iron Age economy. Iron tools were expensive relative to wages — an iron axe head could represent several months of a laborer&rsquo;s income. The man&rsquo;s anguished cry &lsquo;Oh, my master! It was borrowed&rsquo; (<em>ʾăhāh ʾădonî wᵉhûʾ šāʾûl</em>) introduces the economic and social dimension: he is liable for the loss of a borrowed tool, an obligation he cannot meet from his resources as a member of the prophetic guild. The debt-slavery backdrop of ch4:1 is relevant here: an unpayable debt creates a serious social problem.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s action — cutting a stick (<em>wayyiqṣōb ʿēṣ</em>) and throwing it in at the spot — is a sign-act, not a technical solution. Iron does not float under any circumstances; the miracle is the suspended law of density. The stick thrown in may echo the Mosaic pattern of staff-actions (Exod 14:16; 15:25, where Moses throws a stick into bitter water to make it sweet), suggesting Elisha&rsquo;s continuing ministry in the prophetic line from Moses. The act of locating the exact spot first grounds the miracle in the physical specificity of the real event.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;Pick it up&rsquo; (<em>rōmm-lāḵ</em>) — the floating iron is not seized by Elisha but retrieved by the man himself, using his own hand. The miracle does not bypass human agency but enables it. The man reaches out and takes what was lost — the restoration of the tool is the restoration of his social obligation. The brevity of the miracle&rsquo;s resolution (two words in Hebrew) matches its function as a brief sign within a longer narrative section about Aramean warfare.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Aramean king&rsquo;s war strategy depended on ambush and surprise encampment (<em>tiḥneh maḥăneh</em>) — a standard ancient warfare tactic of concealing troop positions before an engagement. The phrase &lsquo;he would consult with his officers&rsquo; (<em>wayyiwwāʿaṣ ʾel-ʿăbādāyw</em>) describes the formal council of war that preceded tactical decisions in ANE armies. The Israelite king&rsquo;s uncanny awareness of Aramean plans sets the stage for the prophetic explanation in vv. 11–12.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Elisha sends warning to the king of Israel: &lsquo;Beware of passing that place — the Arameans are going down there.&rsquo; The prophetic role as military intelligence is extraordinary: Elisha functions as a one-man signals corps, rendering the Aramean strategic advantage — surprise positioning — ineffective. The phrase &lsquo;he warned him&rsquo; (<em>wayyizzāhēr&rsquo;) uses a root associated with prophetic warning; the intelligence is presented not as espionage but as divinely communicated knowledge.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&lsquo;This happened not once or twice&rsquo; (<em>welōʾ-ʾaḥat wᵉlōʾ-šetayim</em>) — the phrase signals repeated occurrences, establishing a pattern before the Aramean king recognizes that there is a systematic intelligence leak. The king of Israel&rsquo;s repeated successful avoidances of Aramean positions is not attributed to his own intelligence network but to the prophetic word — a consistent theme in the Elisha cycle that repositions political and military power relative to prophetic authority.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Aramean king&rsquo;s accusation that &lsquo;one of us&rsquo; (<em>mēʾittānû</em>) is reporting to Israel reflects the logic of counter-intelligence: repeated strategic failure must indicate betrayal. This was a genuine anxiety in ANE court culture, where palace intrigue, divided loyalties, and diplomatic double-dealing were common. The accusation implicitly assumes that the intelligence is human rather than divine — the king cannot conceive of a supernatural source for Israel&rsquo;s foreknowledge.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The officer&rsquo;s explanation — &lsquo;Elisha the prophet who is in Israel tells the king of Israel the very words you speak in your bedroom&rsquo; (<em>yagîd lᵉmelek yiśrāʾēl ʾet-haddᵉbārîm ʾăšer tᵉdabbēr bᵉḥeder miškābekā</em>) — credits prophetic power with a penetration of the innermost privacy of the royal chamber. The bedchamber (<em>ḥeder miškab</em>) is the most private space in the palace; the implication is that no human intelligence could reach there. The Aramean officer&rsquo;s attribution of Elisha&rsquo;s knowledge to supernatural access is the correct explanation — but it makes the prophet a threat to be neutralized, not a resource to be consulted.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Dothan (modern Tell Dothan) is located about 20 km north of Samaria, near a pass in the Samarian hills that served as a major route of ancient travel and trade (cf. Gen 37:17, where Joseph finds his brothers there). The city controlled access to the Jezreel Valley from the south; its location made it a logical point of Aramean military interest. Elisha&rsquo;s presence in Dothan is incidental to the main narrative — he is simply there when the crisis arrives, suggesting that his movements were known and tracked by Aramean intelligence.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Aramean response is disproportionate — horses, chariots, and &lsquo;a great army&rsquo; (<em>ḥayil kābēd</em>) sent to capture a single prophet. The tactical choice of a night arrival and surrounding the city reflects standard siege and capture protocol: arrive under cover of darkness, prevent escape, then seize the target at first light. The military force sent against Elisha is the measure of his perceived threat to Aramean strategic planning; from the Aramean perspective, eliminating the intelligence source is a strategic priority.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The servant&rsquo;s early morning discovery — &lsquo;an army with horses and chariots had surrounded the city&rsquo; — produces the expected response: &lsquo;Oh, my master! What shall we do?&rsquo; (<em>ʾăhāh ʾădonî māh naʿăśeh</em>). The exclamation <em>ʾăhāh</em> is the same as the axe-head man&rsquo;s cry in v5 — a marker of acute distress at a humanly irresolvable situation. The servant&rsquo;s question frames the crisis as a question of available resources: none visible, against an overwhelming military force. Elisha&rsquo;s response reframes the question in terms of invisible reality.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&lsquo;Those who are with us are more than those who are with them&rsquo; (<em>rabbîm ʾăšer ʾittānû miʾăšer ʾittām</em>) is the interpretive key to the following vision. The statement precedes the opened eyes: it is a claim about existing reality, not a reassurance about what will happen. In ANE cosmology, the heavenly armies (celestial or angelic beings associated with YHWH; cf. Josh 5:14, the &lsquo;commander of the LORD&rsquo;s army&rsquo;) were understood as real participants in earthly conflicts. Elisha&rsquo;s claim is not rhetorical comfort; it is a statement of military fact that the servant&rsquo;s normal vision cannot confirm.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s prayer for blindness (<em>siwwᵉrôn</em>) against the descending Aramean army is not the physical blindness that prevents all light perception but a confusion that prevents accurate spatial recognition — they can still travel and follow Elisha but cannot identify where they are. Similar &lsquo;blinding&rsquo; or disorientation of attacking enemies appears in Gen 19:11 (the Sodom mob struck blind by the angels). The miracle is proportionate: the Aramean army is not destroyed but redirected — led into a trap that becomes a feast (v23).</p>",
    "19": "<p>&lsquo;This is not the way, and this is not the city — follow me&rsquo; — Elisha leads the disoriented army to Samaria, the Israelite capital, rather than away from it. The deception is technical: he says he will bring them to the man they are looking for, and he does — he is the man they are looking for, and they arrive in the presence of the king of Israel. The irony is layered: the army sent to capture the prophet is led by the prophet himself into captivity.</p>",
    "20": "<p>In Samaria, the Arameans&rsquo; eyes are opened and they see themselves surrounded — inside the Israelite capital, completely vulnerable. The sight of the blind army in the city center inverts the military logic of the original mission: the besiegers have become the besieged, the hunters the captives, without a blow being struck. The king of Israel, seeing them, immediately asks for permission to strike — the instinct of military advantage is to kill. Elisha&rsquo;s counter-instruction is the pivot of the entire account.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The king&rsquo;s doubled question &lsquo;Shall I strike them down? Shall I strike them down?&rsquo; (<em>hahakkeh ʾakkeh ʾābî hahakkeh ʾakkeh</em>) reflects excitement at the military windfall — the repetition in Hebrew signals urgency and eagerness. The address &lsquo;my father&rsquo; (<em>ʾābî</em>) toward Elisha is a respectful address for a prophetic superior (cf. Naaman&rsquo;s servants in 5:13) and signals the king&rsquo;s deference to prophetic authority even while he presses for military action.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Elisha&rsquo;s refusal to kill is grounded in a principle: &lsquo;You shall not strike them down. Would you kill men you have captured with your sword and bow?&rsquo; The rhetorical logic is that captives taken in battle deserve quarter; the miracle has rendered these men captives, not combatants. The instruction to provide food and water — and to &lsquo;send them away to their master&rsquo; — transforms a military windfall into an act of hospitality. The enemies of Israel become, momentarily, the guests of Israel, fed and released. This is a radical inversion of normal ANE warfare logic.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The great feast prepared for the Aramean army and their subsequent peaceful departure marks the temporary cessation of Aramean raids into Israel. The connection is explicit: &lsquo;The Aramean raiding parties stopped coming into the land of Israel&rsquo; (<em>wᵉlōʾ yāsᵉpû ʿôd geḏûḏê ʾărām lābōʾ bᵉʾereṣ yiśrāʾēl</em>). The ANE context: feeding and releasing prisoners was understood as a covenant-adjacent act — creating a relational bond that temporarily obligated the released party to peaceful behavior. Elisha&rsquo;s strategy uses hospitality as a weapon of a different kind.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Ben-hadad (<em>Ben-hadad</em>, &lsquo;son of Hadad&rsquo; — Hadad being the storm-deity of Aram-Damascus) musters his entire army and besieges Samaria. This is a different and more serious military intervention than the raiding parties of vv. 8–23; a siege of the capital represents a full-scale campaign. Ancient Israelite urban warfare involved investment — encircling a city to cut off supply lines and starve the population into surrender — rather than assault. The siege context establishes the famine conditions of the following verses.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A woman cries out to the king as he passes along the city wall — the posture of a royal supplicant appealing directly to the monarch during a procession or inspection. In the ANE tradition of royal justice, kings were accessible for direct petition by their subjects, at least in theory (cf. 2 Sam 14; 1 Kgs 3:16). The siege context makes this appeal especially poignant: the woman appeals to the king as one who should have power over life and death, in a situation where that power has been utterly stripped from him by the siege.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The king&rsquo;s response &lsquo;If the LORD will not help you, how can I?&rsquo; (<em>ʾal-yhwh lōʾ yôšîʿek mēʾayin ʾôšîʿăkāh</em>) reveals a king who recognizes that the crisis exceeds royal capacity but has lost prophetic connection to the One who could intervene. The rhetorical question from the threshing floor or winepress — pointing to the two sources of grain and grape — indicates that the normal food-distribution systems have been completely exhausted; there is literally nothing left in the agricultural cycle to offer.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The woman&rsquo;s story reveals the extreme cannibalism that siege conditions produced. Deuteronomy 28:53–57 explicitly warns that siege conditions would reduce Israel to eating its own children — a covenant curse invoked for covenant violation. The woman&rsquo;s appeal is perversely legalistic: she had a deal (<em>tᵉnî ʾet-binkā wᵉnōḵᵉlennû hayyôm</em>, &lsquo;give your son and we will eat him today&rsquo;) and her partner did not fulfill it. The grotesque formality of her complaint in the middle of crisis reflects a society where normal moral categories have completely collapsed under siege pressure.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The cooperative cannibalism — two mothers agreeing to kill and eat their respective sons in turn — illustrates the complete breakdown of maternal instinct under famine extremity. The fact that one mother consummated her side of the agreement and the other then concealed her child from being killed marks the moral collapse that Deuteronomy&rsquo;s siege curse predicted. Josephus (<em>Jewish War</em> 6.193–213) describes similarly horrific events during the Roman siege of Jerusalem in 70 CE, confirming that such extremities occurred in actual siege conditions and were not merely rhetorical.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The king&rsquo;s tearing of his garments reveals that he is wearing sackcloth (<em>wᵉhinnēh-śaq ʿal-bᵉśārô mittāḥat</em>) underneath his royal clothing — he is already in a state of mourning, hidden from public view. This detail humanizes the king while pointing to his spiritual bankruptcy: he mourns privately while the prophetic solution (Elisha) is available. The public revelation of his sackcloth follows his hearing of the woman&rsquo;s story; his mourning becomes external and visible, setting the stage for his blaming of Elisha.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The king&rsquo;s oath against Elisha — &lsquo;May God deal with me, however severely, if the head of Elisha son of Shaphat remains on his head today&rsquo; — is an imprecation formula (<em>kōh yᵃʿăśeh-lî ʾĕlōhîm wᵉkōh yōsip</em>) committing him to Elisha&rsquo;s execution. The blame-transfer is characteristic of kings under siege in the Hebrew narratives: when prayer and prophecy have not produced relief, the prophet becomes the scapegoat. The irony is that Elisha has been the sole source of Israel&rsquo;s military advantage; his death would eliminate any remaining prophetic defense.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Elisha, sitting with the elders, receives prophetic foreknowledge that the king is sending an executioner. His description of the king as &lsquo;this son of a murderer&rsquo; (<em>ben-hamᵉrassēaḥ</em>) — or possibly &lsquo;son of a murderer&rsquo; referring to the king&rsquo;s father — is a stark prophetic denunciation within the prophetic assembly. The instruction to hold the door against the king&rsquo;s messenger and then the note that &lsquo;the king&rsquo;s own footsteps follow&rsquo; behind his messenger suggests that the king is coming in person, perhaps having second thoughts about the execution order.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The king&rsquo;s despairing declaration &lsquo;This disaster is from the LORD — why should I wait any longer for the LORD?&rsquo; (<em>hinnēh-zōʾt hārāʿāh mēʾēt yhwh māh ʾôḥil layhwh ʿôd</em>) is a statement of theological crisis — he attributes the famine-siege to YHWH while simultaneously declaring prophetic expectation futile. The siege has broken the king&rsquo;s faith in prophetic intercession. His question sets the stage for Elisha&rsquo;s oracle in 7:1, which immediately follows: the answer to &lsquo;why wait?&rsquo; will be the dramatic provision of ch7.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2kings', existing)
    for ch in ['4', '5', '6']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
